00:28:38.028 --> 00:28:40.497
the tray as a palette itself.

00:28:40.497 --> 00:28:50.077
Ellen: Do you wanna ask...get some more questions?

00:28:50.077 --> 00:28:52.467
Diana: Yeah.

00:28:52.467 --> 00:28:59.357
Oh, this is a good question FF Boda asks,
"What are the main challenges of contemporary

00:28:59.357 --> 00:29:01.487
art conservation?"

00:29:01.487 --> 00:29:03.057
It's a really good question.

00:29:03.057 --> 00:29:04.057
Ellen: Yeah.

00:29:04.057 --> 00:29:11.207
Contemporary art conservation, as opposed
to more traditional forms of conservation.

00:29:11.207 --> 00:29:16.888
Well, first off, there are a lot more materials
since the Second World War.

00:29:16.888 --> 00:29:25.538
So we're dealing with a huge range of polymers
and plastics that really haven't been tested

00:29:25.538 --> 00:29:28.448
by time.

00:29:28.448 --> 00:29:32.908
We don't know how they're going to age and
how they get along with other materials.

00:29:32.908 --> 00:29:38.678
So the number of materials that we're responsible
for is infinitely larger than it would be

00:29:38.678 --> 00:29:44.237
for somebody working on objects from the early
20th century and before.

00:29:44.237 --> 00:29:48.317
Diana: Yeah, we're also dealing with…something

00:29:48.317 --> 00:29:53.638
that's really cool is the artists might still
be alive.

00:29:53.638 --> 00:30:01.008
And so documenting the artist's intent and
documenting just how the artist works might

00:30:01.008 --> 00:30:03.878
be part of our documentation process.

00:30:03.878 --> 00:30:07.678
Whereas before, obviously, that was impossible.

00:30:07.678 --> 00:30:13.518
So it's a really exciting time and I think
we're all kind of learning as we go.

00:30:13.518 --> 00:30:17.247
Ellen: Yeah, and the ethics aren't as cut

00:30:17.247 --> 00:30:18.247
and dry, right?

00:30:18.247 --> 00:30:19.247
Diana: Yeah.

00:30:19.247 --> 00:30:22.658
Ellen: We're not always trying to preserve

00:30:22.658 --> 00:30:23.658
the material.

00:30:23.658 --> 00:30:29.058
We're not as precious about the material as
we might have been for more traditional objects.

00:30:29.058 --> 00:30:34.217
Because there are some objects that demand
they be remade every time they're shown and

00:30:34.217 --> 00:30:39.548
there are others whose material is just disintegrating.

00:30:39.548 --> 00:30:50.337
So it's…it would be preferable in some cases
to actually remake or replicate than to preserve

00:30:50.337 --> 00:30:52.467
that material.

00:30:52.467 --> 00:30:56.867
Diana: Yeah, maybe like, for example, our

00:30:56.867 --> 00:31:06.058
colleague, Megan, was working on…Megan Randall
was working on a wax leg by Robert Gober,

00:31:06.058 --> 00:31:08.237
and I wasn't here at the time so I don't know
if you…

00:31:08.237 --> 00:31:09.237
Ellen: Right.

00:31:09.237 --> 00:31:13.548
The wax leg had little human hair sticking
out of it.

00:31:13.548 --> 00:31:17.918
And it goes into…the part of the installation
is it goes into a bathtub and bath water runs

00:31:17.918 --> 00:31:24.378
over it and the hairs, from the pressure of
the water, get dislodged and pulled out.

00:31:24.378 --> 00:31:32.538
So rather than fishing out those scuzzy hairs
in the bath and finding out where they came

00:31:32.538 --> 00:31:37.468
from and putting them back in place, it was
preferable from the Gober Studio and our curatorial

00:31:37.468 --> 00:31:42.328
team to replace that hair with a new hair
that they supplied Megan.

00:31:42.328 --> 00:31:47.597
And they... and someone from the studio came
and trained her on how to insert human hair

00:31:47.597 --> 00:31:53.148
into a wax leg and it was really disgusting.

00:31:53.148 --> 00:31:54.678
Diana: Yeah, so, I mean, that's something

00:31:54.678 --> 00:31:55.827
totally new.

00:31:55.827 --> 00:31:56.997
It's really fun.

00:31:56.997 --> 00:31:59.528
Ellen: Right, the learning curve is very steep,

00:31:59.528 --> 00:32:01.518
which is what makes it interesting.

00:32:01.518 --> 00:32:02.538
Diana: Yes.

00:32:02.538 --> 00:32:03.558
Ellen: Yeah.

00:32:03.558 --> 00:32:04.577
All right.

00:32:04.577 --> 00:32:10.938
We've got another live question here from
Cat, "How has conservation changed in your

00:32:10.938 --> 00:32:11.938
careers?

00:32:11.938 --> 00:32:14.197
Materials and techniques evolve.

00:32:14.197 --> 00:32:19.567
Have past conservators unknowingly done damage
to art?"

00:32:19.567 --> 00:32:26.817
Two great questions and the first one is related
to what we were just discussing, how there's

00:32:26.817 --> 00:32:28.518
all these new materials and techniques.

00:32:28.518 --> 00:32:36.058
I think we're lucky here at MoMA because we
have our science conservation department upstairs.

00:32:36.058 --> 00:32:40.748
And so if we have materials that we...that
come in with a new acquisition, we're not

00:32:40.748 --> 00:32:45.468
sure what they are how they might react, we
can send them up for analysis.

00:32:45.468 --> 00:32:52.268
And that can inform the materials we use and
our understanding of that artist's practice.

00:32:52.268 --> 00:32:58.858
Diana: Yeah, and also that the materials we

00:32:58.858 --> 00:33:03.597
use, because of new plastics and new resins
and things like that, like you were saying,

00:33:03.597 --> 00:33:10.788
we have such a broader choice when it comes
to like varnishing or when it comes to adhesive.

00:33:10.788 --> 00:33:15.977
And so I think that feeds into the second
question.

00:33:15.977 --> 00:33:22.548
I don't think it's fair to say that past conservators
did damage at all.

00:33:22.548 --> 00:33:27.628
I think they just didn't have the same tools
that we might have now.

00:33:27.628 --> 00:33:31.727
So they were doing their best at the time
with what they were...what they had around

00:33:31.727 --> 00:33:33.308
them to use.

00:33:33.308 --> 00:33:36.207
Ellen: Right, but yeah, as we said before,

00:33:36.207 --> 00:33:43.807
a lot of what we do is undoing past restoration
attempts that…where materials have failed

00:33:43.807 --> 00:33:45.097
and undoubtedly…

00:33:45.097 --> 00:33:46.847
Diana: That will happen.

00:33:46.847 --> 00:33:50.717
Ellen: We'll be on the other end of the equation

00:33:50.717 --> 00:33:52.008
in the future.

00:33:52.008 --> 00:33:55.308
Hopefully less and less as we learn more and
more.

00:33:55.308 --> 00:34:00.379
But at the same time, the materials are evolving
as our understanding of them is.

00:34:00.379 --> 00:34:02.228
So it's hard to keep up.

00:34:02.228 --> 00:34:07.108
Diana: But we try our best.

00:34:07.108 --> 00:34:11.188
Ellen: We try our best.

00:34:11.188 --> 00:34:15.057
Diana: Oh, this one's for Ellen.

00:34:15.057 --> 00:34:21.508
Alexis asks, and this is in regards to conserving
a Frank Lloyd Wright statue, "Okay, but what

00:34:21.508 --> 00:34:24.268
happened to her head restoration?"

00:34:24.268 --> 00:34:25.268
Rolling face.

00:34:25.268 --> 00:34:26.268
Ellen: Rolling eye emoji.

00:34:26.268 --> 00:34:27.608
Diana: Rolling eyes emoji.

00:34:27.608 --> 00:34:28.658
Ellen: Rolling face?

00:34:28.658 --> 00:34:30.508
Diana: So what did happen to her head?

00:34:30.508 --> 00:34:35.398
Ellen: Yeah, so yeah, Alexis Thomas is among,

00:34:35.398 --> 00:34:40.578
I think, several viewers who watched this
video that we posted about this Frank Lloyd

00:34:40.578 --> 00:34:42.258
Wright sprite with a missing head.

00:34:42.258 --> 00:34:45.008
And it was all about our restoration of this
headless sprite.

00:34:45.008 --> 00:34:48.318
But at the end of the video, we hadn't replaced
the head.

00:34:48.318 --> 00:34:53.018
We were focused on this crack system at her
midsection.

00:34:53.018 --> 00:35:00.818
And yeah, we never did replace the head and
that's because we were preparing this work

00:35:00.818 --> 00:35:06.958
for an exhibition that didn't really require
a perfect restoration.

00:35:06.958 --> 00:35:13.888
It was for "Frank Lloyd Wright at 150: Unpacking
the Archive."

00:35:13.888 --> 00:35:19.238
And so it's all about how the archive, Frank
Lloyd Wright's archive, came to MoMA in Columbia,

00:35:19.238 --> 00:35:24.088
and how we were interpreting the objects in
that archive as sort of raw data.

00:35:24.088 --> 00:35:27.278
So to the curator, Barry Bergdoll, it wasn't

00:35:27.278 --> 00:35:35.718
all that important that presenting this sprite,
we were presenting it as this entire piece

00:35:35.718 --> 00:35:44.788
because we received a lot of objects that
were in" So you can understand how a partial

00:35:44.788 --> 00:35:48.558
restoration might be acceptable in this presentation.

00:35:48.558 --> 00:35:53.138
But that's not to say that we won't restore
the head in the future.

00:35:53.138 --> 00:35:58.478
And I can imagine a lot of different types
of exhibitions where we would want to, like

00:35:58.478 --> 00:36:03.178
one about Midway Gardens, the project the
sprite came from.

00:36:03.178 --> 00:36:08.578
And how Frank Lloyd Wright worked with concrete
and how he cast concrete.

00:36:08.578 --> 00:36:14.358
In that sort of presentation, it might be
nice to show his intended results.

00:36:14.358 --> 00:36:19.018
Diana: But, if you were to restore the head,

00:36:19.018 --> 00:36:21.638
you wouldn't just invent a head right?

00:36:21.638 --> 00:36:28.158
You would look at a lot of documentation and
other sprites that still exist and…

00:36:28.158 --> 00:36:30.288
Ellen: Yeah, that's a good point.

00:36:30.288 --> 00:36:35.528
There is an abundance of historical evidence
of what that head looked like and other existing

00:36:35.528 --> 00:36:36.528
heads.

00:36:36.528 --> 00:36:42.308
So we could definitely use that, molds of
those head scans of those heads to inform

00:36:42.308 --> 00:36:49.028
how we recreate ours because this one sprite
came from…is one of 20 or so that came from

00:36:49.028 --> 00:36:50.738
the same mold.

00:36:50.738 --> 00:36:52.928
So that's lucky for us.

00:36:52.928 --> 00:36:53.928
Diana: Yeah.

00:36:53.928 --> 00:36:54.928
Ellen: If we didn't have any evidence of the

00:36:54.928 --> 00:36:59.038
head, then we might not attempt to restore
it, period.

00:36:59.038 --> 00:37:03.738
I have another live question.

00:37:03.738 --> 00:37:12.438
Enigma writes, "Is all of the work/restoration
due to age-related reasons?

00:37:12.438 --> 00:37:16.318
Do things ever happen because of accidents
or anything like that?"

00:37:16.318 --> 00:37:17.318
Diana: That's a really good question.

00:37:17.318 --> 00:37:21.358
Ellen: Is all restoration related to age reasons?

00:37:21.358 --> 00:37:23.418
Yes, yeah.

00:37:23.418 --> 00:37:25.488
Diana: Yeah.

00:37:25.488 --> 00:37:31.498
Ellen: I'd say, I don't know, a quarter of

00:37:31.498 --> 00:37:36.738
the works that come to our lab are because
of damages and not because of deterioration.

00:37:36.738 --> 00:37:41.508
Because of handling or something fell off
of its pedestal due to vibrations.

00:37:41.508 --> 00:37:45.088
Diana: Yeah, and sometimes age makes an artwork

00:37:45.088 --> 00:37:48.048
more susceptible to damage.

00:37:48.048 --> 00:37:49.878
So that's important to think about.

00:37:49.878 --> 00:37:54.148
But, yeah, sometimes we do have to fix careless
accidents.

00:37:54.148 --> 00:37:55.948
Ellen: Accidents.

00:37:55.948 --> 00:38:04.098
The euphemism we use is "visitor interaction"
for when a work has been damaged due to an

00:38:04.098 --> 00:38:09.228
overzealous visitor or a clumsy visitor who
was taking a selfie.

00:38:09.228 --> 00:38:12.768
Diana: Yeah, but that was that's a really

00:38:12.768 --> 00:38:15.478
good question.

00:38:15.478 --> 00:38:20.838
Ellen: Another live question from Devon Colley,

00:38:20.838 --> 00:38:25.258
"Are either of you and your colleagues practicing
contemporary artists?"

00:38:25.258 --> 00:38:26.258
No.

00:38:26.258 --> 00:38:32.238
"And if yes, does being a conservator positively
or negatively impact your art-making career?"

00:38:32.238 --> 00:38:37.058
Diana: Yes, so I was actually a painter before

00:38:37.058 --> 00:38:38.508
I became a conservator.

00:38:38.508 --> 00:38:39.508
Ellen: Really?

00:38:39.508 --> 00:38:42.208
Diana: Yes, I was an oil painter and…

00:38:42.208 --> 00:38:44.978
Ellen: Like, figurative or abstract?

00:38:44.978 --> 00:38:47.808
Diana: I would say figurative but surreal.

00:38:47.808 --> 00:38:48.858
Ellen: Cool.

00:38:48.858 --> 00:38:52.558
Diana: But the problem is I'm actually currently

00:38:52.558 --> 00:38:59.728
still a graduate student and the conservation
program is quite intense and you have to give

00:38:59.728 --> 00:39:01.018
a lot of your time to it.

00:39:01.018 --> 00:39:07.298
So in that sense, negatively affected my practice
because I just don't have time to paint.

00:39:07.298 --> 00:39:13.738
But I think after I've graduated this summer,
I will go back to making art.

00:39:13.738 --> 00:39:20.178
And I think I'll honestly keep doing what
I was doing before.

00:39:20.178 --> 00:39:23.128
Ellen: It's had no impact on you.

00:39:23.128 --> 00:39:26.308
Diana: It had no…it's…I think we learn

00:39:26.308 --> 00:39:33.858
a lot of traditional techniques during school
so we learn how certain paintings were made,

00:39:33.858 --> 00:39:35.448
how certain sculptures were made.

00:39:35.448 --> 00:39:40.358
And I think, yeah, maybe I'll have picked
up a little bit of that my own practice.

00:39:40.358 --> 00:39:49.028
But I know…yeah, I know other conservators
are really influenced by, say, old master

00:39:49.028 --> 00:39:50.028
artists.

00:39:50.028 --> 00:39:51.458
Ellen: Yeah, and I'm not an artist.

00:39:51.458 --> 00:39:57.728
I loved my studio art classes, I love working
with my hands and honing a skill.

00:39:57.728 --> 00:40:04.298
But I always had trouble with coming up with
a concept facing a blank page.

00:40:04.298 --> 00:40:09.138
That was never my strength and I don't have
any inclination to create in that way.

00:40:09.138 --> 00:40:17.448
So conservation is perfect because the art's
already there and I can work within that framing.

00:40:17.448 --> 00:40:21.488
But I think it has…I think conservation,
working conservation has impacted the way

00:40:21.488 --> 00:40:22.488
I view art.

00:40:22.488 --> 00:40:28.288
I think it makes it much harder just to appreciate
a painting or sculpture.

00:40:28.288 --> 00:40:35.618
If you can see the damages and knowledge of
the types of damages that can happen and how…what

00:40:35.618 --> 00:40:40.678
old restoration looks like, I think, really
I can't un-see that now when I look…

00:40:40.678 --> 00:40:41.678
Diana: Absolutely.

00:40:41.678 --> 00:40:43.798
Ellen: …at the work that has any sort of

00:40:43.798 --> 00:40:44.798
damage.

00:40:44.798 --> 00:40:46.348
Diana: Well, and I like that point.

00:40:46.348 --> 00:40:52.528
I think conservation, going through the program
and learning all about materials has really

00:40:52.528 --> 00:40:58.588
made me love modern and contemporary art so
much more than I did before.

00:40:58.588 --> 00:41:05.348
Because I'm so much more aware of the importance
of materials and the importance of different

00:41:05.348 --> 00:41:09.838
techniques and subtle things like that, that
I might not have noticed before.

00:41:09.838 --> 00:41:16.208
So when you're in a gallery next time, really
look at the materials and the choices the

00:41:16.208 --> 00:41:18.838
artist made on how they use those materials.

00:41:18.838 --> 00:41:19.998
Should we...?

